_**PAW Patrol**_ is a Canadian [CGI](/wiki/Computer-generated_imagery
"Computer-generated imagery")–[animated television
series](/wiki/Animated_series "Animated series") created by [Keith
Chapman](/wiki/Keith_Chapman "Keith Chapman"). It is produced by [Spin Master
Entertainment](/wiki/Spin_Master "Spin Master") in association with
[TVOntario](/wiki/TVOntario "TVOntario") and Nickelodeon, with animation
provided by [Guru Studio](/wiki/Guru_Studio "Guru Studio"). In Canada, the
series is primarily broadcast on TVOntario, which first ran previews of the
show in August 2013. The series first aired on [Nickelodeon](/wiki/Nickelodeon
"Nickelodeon") in the United States on August 12, 2013.

The series focuses on a boy named Ryder who leads a pack of [search and rescue
dogs](/wiki/Search_and_rescue_dog "Search and rescue dog") known as the PAW
Patrol. They work together on missions to protect the shoreside community of
Adventure Bay. Each dog has a specific set of skills based on a real-life
profession, such as a [firefighter](/wiki/Firefighter "Firefighter") and a
[police officer](/wiki/Police_officer "Police officer"). They all reside in
[doghouses](/wiki/Doghouse "Doghouse") that can transform into customized
vehicles when necessary. They are also equipped with backpacks called "pup
packs" that contain tools that relate to the pups' jobs.

Spin Master has developed the show into a [media
franchise](/wiki/Media_franchise "Media franchise") and released an ongoing
line of toys based on it. _PAW Patrol_ toy sales have generated millions of
dollars in revenue for the corporation and increased Spin Master's presence in
the preschool toy market.[1] The show, and its associated products, have
received a variety of awards and nominations from associations such as the
[Academy of Canadian Cinema &
Television](/wiki/Academy_of_Canadian_Cinema_%26_Television "Academy of
Canadian Cinema & Television") and the [Academy of Television Arts &
Sciences](/wiki/Academy_of_Television_Arts_%26_Sciences "Academy of Television
Arts & Sciences").

## Format[[edit](/w/index.php?title=PAW_Patrol&action=edit&section=1 "Edit
section: Format")]

Each episode of _PAW Patrol_ follows a similar pattern and features recurring
themes. Episodes normally open with a scene depicting the dogs going about
their everyday lives, often playing with [dog toys](/wiki/Dog_toy "Dog toy")
or engaging in activities at the local playground. Ryder, a ten-year-old boy,
is advised of a problem by receiving a call for help or by witnessing a
situation himself. His most frequent caller is an accident-prone [marine
biologist](/wiki/Marine_biology "Marine biology") named Cap'n Turbot, who
knows much about Adventure Bay's wildlife. Ryder always alerts the dogs via
their blinking [pet tags](/wiki/Pet_tag "Pet tag"). The team members report to
their base, the Lookout, and enter its elevator. Marshall typically arrives
last causing a humorous mishap that makes the other dogs laugh as the elevator
rises. When they reach the top floor, they arrange themselves in a line. Chase
announces that the team is ready for action as Ryder tells the pups what has
happened. He chooses several members of the team, normally two [first
responders](/wiki/First_responder "First responder"), to help solve whatever
problem has emerged. They ride a slide down to their vehicles and complete
their mission. When they have finished, Ryder says his catchphrase: "Whenever
you're in trouble, just yelp for help!", and congratulates the pups.

section: PAW Patrol members")]

[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/2/27/PAW_Patrol_main_characters%2C_cast_promo_art.png)](/wiki/File:PAW_Patrol_main_characters,_cast_promo_art.png)

#### Original
members[[edit](/w/index.php?title=PAW_Patrol&action=edit&section=5 "Edit
section: Original members")]

  * Ryder is the human leader of the PAW Patrol. He is a ten-year-old boy who gives the dogs their mission instructions and builds the vehicles and equipment they use. His vehicle is an [ATV](/wiki/All-terrain_vehicle "All-terrain vehicle"). He is the only character to be featured in every mission, and the only member to use his vehicle in every episode. He was voiced by Owen Mason from 2013–2015, by Elijha Hammill from 2015–2016, and by Jaxon Mercey from 2016 onward.
  * Marshall is a [Dalmatian](/wiki/Dalmatian_\(dog\) "Dalmatian \(dog\)"). He serves as a firedog and medic. His vehicle is a [fire engine](/wiki/Fire_engine "Fire engine"), which transforms into an [ambulance](/wiki/Ambulance "Ambulance"). He is known for being exceptionally clumsy. A running gag in every episode is that Marshall will encounter some kind of humorous problem while trying to enter the PAW Patrol's elevator. His catchphrase after one of these mishaps is often "I'm good." He was voiced by [Gage Munroe](/wiki/Gage_Munroe "Gage Munroe") from 2013–2014 and by Drew Davis from 2014 onward.
  * Rubble is an [English bulldog](/wiki/English_bulldog "English bulldog"). He serves as a construction dog. His vehicle is a [bulldozer](/wiki/Bulldozer "Bulldozer"). He is often a source of comic relief and usually makes jokes or comments about his love of eating. He is voiced by Devan Cohen.
  * Chase is a [German Shepherd](/wiki/German_Shepherd "German Shepherd"). He serves as a police and spy dog. His vehicle is a [cruiser](/wiki/Police_car "Police car"). He is the most mature of the dogs, and will always announce "Ready for action, Ryder, sir!" when the PAW Patrol is called on a mission. He was voiced by Tristan Samuel from 2013–2014, by Max Calinescu from 2014–2018, and by Justin Kelley from 2018 onward.
  * Rocky is a grey-and-white [mongrel](/wiki/Mongrel "Mongrel") of an unspecified breed. He serves as a recycling dog. His vehicle is a recycling truck, which can also transform into a salvage tugboat. A running gag in the series is Rocky's irrational fear of water to the point where he refuses to bathe. He was voiced by Stuart Ralston from 2013–2015 and by Samuel Faraci from 2015 onward.
  * Zuma is a [chocolate Labrador retriever](/wiki/Labrador_Retriever "Labrador Retriever"). He serves as an aquatic rescue pup. His vehicle is a [hovercraft](/wiki/Hovercraft "Hovercraft"), which can also convert into a [submarine](/wiki/Submarine "Submarine"). He was voiced by Alex Thorne from 2013–2017 and by Carter Thorne from 2017 onward.
  * Skye is a [cockapoo](/wiki/Cockapoo "Cockapoo"). She serves as an aviator. Her vehicle is a [helicopter](/wiki/Helicopter "Helicopter"), and she has wings built into her backpack. She is voiced by Kallan Holley.

#### Later members[[edit](/w/index.php?title=PAW_Patrol&action=edit&section=6
"Edit section: Later members")]

  * Cap'n Turbot is the PAW Patrol's most frequent caller, who serves as an occasional member of the team in the Merpup-themed special episodes. He is a smart marine biologist and the watchman of Adventure Bay. His main vehicle is a boat called the _Flounder_. In the second season, an orange [diving bell](/wiki/Diving_bell "Diving bell") is introduced as his second vehicle. He is the team's best human friend and their source of information on all kinds of wildlife in the bay. He is voiced by [Ron Pardo](/wiki/Ron_Pardo "Ron Pardo"). Along with Everest, Cap'n Turbot was added to the opening theme in [season three](/wiki/List_of_PAW_Patrol_episodes#Season_3_\(2015–2017\) "List of PAW Patrol episodes").
  * Everest is a [Siberian husky](/wiki/Siberian_husky "Siberian husky") who serves as a snow rescue dog in emergencies relating to snow or ice. Her vehicle is a [snowmobile](/wiki/Snowmobile "Snowmobile"). Like Tracker, she does not stay with the PAW Patrol and instead lives at Adventure Bay's ski resort, but will answer a call for assistance whenever her services are needed. She is voiced by Berkley Silverman. Everest, along with Cap'n Turbot, was added to the opening theme in [season three](/wiki/List_of_PAW_Patrol_episodes#Season_3_\(2015–2017\) "List of PAW Patrol episodes").
  * Tracker is a brown-and-white [chihuahua](/wiki/Chihuahua_\(dog\) "Chihuahua \(dog\)") who serves as a jungle rescue pup. His vehicle is a [Jeep](/wiki/Jeep "Jeep"), and he is bilingual, speaking fluently in [Spanish](/wiki/Spanish_language "Spanish language") and English. Like Everest, he does not stay with the PAW Patrol and instead resides in the jungle with his human caretaker, a boy named Carlos. He is voiced by David Lopez. As of season five, he and Robo-Dog have not been added to the opening theme.
  * Robo-Dog is a robotic dog introduced in "Pups Save Ryder's Robot." He serves as the driver of the PAW Patrol's multi-member vehicles. Unlike the other pups, Robo-Dog does not speak in sentences and only communicates through barks. His vehicle (the PAW Patroller) was added to the opening theme in [season three](/wiki/List_of_PAW_Patrol_episodes#Season_3_\(2015–2017\) "List of PAW Patrol episodes"), but Robo-Dog himself does not appear.

### Recurring[[edit](/w/index.php?title=PAW_Patrol&action=edit&section=7 "Edit
section: Recurring")]

  * Mayor Goodway is the overdramatic but friendly mayor of Adventure Bay. She owns a pet chicken named Chickaletta, which she keeps in her purse. She shares a rivalry with Mayor Humdinger of the neighbouring town Foggy Bottom. She is voiced by Deann Degruijter.
  * Chickaletta is the mayor's pet chicken. She is not quick-witted or observant and often unintentionally causes trouble for herself and Mayor Goodway. She is introduced in "Pup Pup and Away" when she jumps into Mayor Goodway's purse during a hot air balloon race.
  * Francois Turbot is Cap'n Turbot's cousin and sidekick, who lives with him in the Seal Island lighthouse. He is very self-centered and loves to show off, but also cares deeply about animals. Francois works as a zoologist, artist, and nature photographer. He has a thick [French](/wiki/French_language "French language") accent and often uses French phrases in place of English words. He is voiced by Peter Cugno.
  * Wally is Cap'n Turbot's pet walrus, who lives in the waters surrounding Seal Island. He has a wife named Walinda and an unnamed baby child. Although he cannot talk, Ryder and Cap'n Turbot can understand Wally when he communicates by barking and moving his flippers.
  * Mayor Humdinger is the mayor of a neighbouring town called Foggy Bottom. He is Mayor Goodway's rival who spends most of his time devising unfair schemes to make his town seem better than Adventure Bay. He lives in a cave and leads a team of troublesome cats called the Kitten Catastrophe Crew. He is voiced by [Ron Pardo](/wiki/Ron_Pardo "Ron Pardo").
  * The Kitten Catastrophe Crew is Mayor Humdinger's group of kittens who closely resemble the six original PAW Patrol pups. Each one is equipped with a uniform and a tool pack that mirror a particular pup's outfits and abilities.
  * Katie is a girl Ryder's age. She runs Adventure Bay's pet clinic and owns a cat named Cali. She is voiced by Katherine Forrester.
  * Mr. Porter is a grocer in Adventure Bay. He is voiced by Blair Williams.
  * Alex Porter is Mr. Porter's young grandson. He is voiced by Christian Distefano.
  * Farmer Yumi and Farmer Al are two married farmers who live near Adventure Bay. They own a barn and have several animals, such as a pair of pigs and a cow. Farmer Yumi was voiced by Hiromi Okuyama from 2013–2014 and by Stephany Seki from 2014 onward. Farmer Al is voiced by [Ron Pardo](/wiki/Ron_Pardo "Ron Pardo").
  * Jake is the owner of a ski resort near Adventure Bay. He becomes Everest's caretaker after she is introduced. He is voiced by [Scott McCord](/wiki/Scott_McCord "Scott McCord").
  * Carlos is a jungle explorer who is Tracker's caretaker. He was voiced by Lucius Hoyos and later by Jaiden Cannatelli.
  * Danny is a daredevil boy who appears in the third season episode "Pups Save Daring Danny X".
  * Sweetie is a villainous pup and the pet of the Princess of Barkingburg. She acts as an antagonist in "Mission PAW"-themed episodes in the fourth season. She has a chew toy named Busby that she treats as a robot minion. She is voiced by Anya Cooke.

## Production[[edit](/w/index.php?title=PAW_Patrol&action=edit&section=8 "Edit
section: Production")]

According to Spin Master, the concept for _PAW Patrol_ stemmed from a
prototype for a transforming truck toy that Spin Master co-founder [Ronnen
Harary](/wiki/Ronnen_Harary "Ronnen Harary") designed in 2010.[5] Later the
same year, the company requested proposals for a television show based on the
transforming toy, and accepted one from _[Bob the
Builder](/wiki/Bob_the_Builder "Bob the Builder")_ creator Keith Chapman.
Chapman sketched early designs of the PAW Patrol team under the working title
_Raffi & the Rescue Dogs_. Spin Master hired toy designers to develop the
format further; after the concept was in place, they began designing
merchandise.[6]

Chapman's original pitch focused on the idea that the six PAW Patrol dogs were
rescued by Ryder before joining the team. [Scott Kraft](/wiki/Scott_Kraft
"Scott Kraft"), the show's first writer, and Jamie Whitney, the show's first
director, decided to abandon the rescued dog theme in 2012. The name of the
series' protagonist, Ryder, was changed multiple times during production; he
was originally called Raffi, Roddy, and Robbie before Spin Master settled on
Ryder.

[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/7/7b/PAW_Patrol_original_character_designs.png/300px-
PAW_Patrol_original_character_designs.png)](/wiki/File:PAW_Patrol_original_character_designs.png)

[](/wiki/File:PAW_Patrol_original_character_designs.png "Enlarge")

Early models of the _PAW Patrol_ pups

According to a 2017 Spin Master interview, "everything pup-related was debated
endlessly: names, sizes, ages, breeds."[7] The pups' designs underwent major
changes after Chapman's pitch; they were originally very realistic, with
unique fur and textures based on their breeds, but they were later simplified
and made more cartoonish. The visual appearance of Cap'n Turbot, mainly his
distinctive bead eyes and large nose, was based on the design of Chapman's Bob
the Builder character. Ryder's hairstyle was based on that of Ronnen
Harary.[7]

In January 2012, Spin Master began approaching television broadcasters. The
company negotiated a broadcast partnership with Nickelodeon, and the network
first announced that it had picked up _PAW Patrol_ at the 2013 Licensing Expo
in Las Vegas, Nevada.[8] The series became Spin Master's first solely-owned
[intellectual property](/wiki/Intellectual_property "Intellectual property")
(IP)[9] once it was released in August 2013.[10]

Since it began production, the show's animation has been provided by [Guru
Studio](/wiki/Guru_Studio "Guru Studio"). In a 2016 interview with _[Maclean's
Magazine](/wiki/Maclean%27s "Maclean's")_, Guru president Frank Falcone stated
that his studio's animators were originally suspicious of the show's
"[toyetic](/wiki/Toyetic "Toyetic")" concept.[11] The series' rock-
inspired[12] [original score](/wiki/Film_score "Film score") was composed by
the Ontario-based group [Voodoo Highway Music &
Post](/wiki/Voodoo_Highway_Music_%26_Post_Inc. "Voodoo Highway Music & Post
Inc."). The opening theme song, and the ending song used in each episode
include vocals performed by Scott Simons.

With each season of the show, new supporting characters and themes are
introduced in its episodes. In a May 2016 interview for the _[Toronto
Star](/wiki/Toronto_Star "Toronto Star")_ , Spin Master president Ben Gadbois
stated that his company would continue to introduce additional characters and
concepts to increase the franchise's longevity and to expand upon the success
of tie-in merchandise.[13] In August of the same year, Ronnen Harary explained
that these changes were intended to keep the show's content "fresh" and
"relevant".[14]

### Broadcast[[edit](/w/index.php?title=PAW_Patrol&action=edit&section=10
"Edit section: Broadcast")]

The series has been sold to TV networks in over 160 countries.[15]

In Canada, the series is primarily shown on [TVOntario](/wiki/TVOntario
"TVOntario") during the [TVOKids](/wiki/TVOKids "TVOKids") block.[16]
[Knowledge Network](/wiki/Knowledge_Network "Knowledge Network"), [Télé-
Québec](/wiki/T%C3%A9l%C3%A9-Qu%C3%A9bec "Télé-Québec") and [City
Saskatchewan](/wiki/City_Saskatchewan "City Saskatchewan") also air reruns of
the show in different Canadian provinces. In the United States, the series is
aired on [Nickelodeon](/wiki/Nickelodeon "Nickelodeon")'s [Nick Jr.
block](/wiki/Nick_Jr._\(block\) "Nick Jr. \(block\)") with reruns on the [Nick
Jr. channel](/wiki/Nick_Jr. "Nick Jr.").

As required for Canadian programs aired on federally-funded networks, _PAW
Patrol_ has been dubbed in French for Quebec broadcasts and for its broadcast
in France on [TF1](/wiki/TF1 "TF1").[17] [Canal Panda](/wiki/Canal_Panda
"Canal Panda") airs a [European Portuguese](/wiki/European_Portuguese
"European Portuguese") dub.[18] and it aired on [MBC3](/wiki/MBC3 "MBC3") in
the Middle East. A [British English](/wiki/British_English "British English")
dub, which uses the same scripts as the Canadian version with minor changes,
is shown on [Channel 5](/wiki/Channel_5_\(UK\) "Channel 5 \(UK\)") and [Nick
Jr. UK](/wiki/Nick_Jr._\(UK_and_Ireland\) "Nick Jr. \(UK and Ireland\)").[19]
[Anione](https://ko.wikipedia.org/wiki/%EC%95%A0%EB%8B%88%EC%9B%90 "ko:애니원"),
[JEI TV](https://ko.wikipedia.org/wiki/%EC%9E%AC%EB%8A%A5TV "ko:재능TV"), and
[KBS](/wiki/Korean_Broadcasting_System "Korean Broadcasting System") have all
broadcast the [Korean](/wiki/Korean_language "Korean language")-dubbed
version.[20] The show has been aired in the [Icelandic
language](/wiki/Icelandic_language "Icelandic language") on Iceland's public
broadcaster [RÚV](/wiki/R%C3%9AV "RÚV") since 2015.[21] The first two seasons
were shown in [Finnish](/wiki/Finnish_language "Finnish language") on [Yle
TV2](/wiki/Yle_TV2 "Yle TV2").[22] The [video on demand](/wiki/Video_on_demand
"Video on demand") platform [Le.com](/wiki/Le.com "Le.com") obtained broadcast
rights for a [Mandarin Chinese](/wiki/Mandarin_Chinese "Mandarin
Chinese")-dubbed version of _PAW Patrol_ in April 2016.[23] it will air on
[MiniMini+](/wiki/MiniMini%2B "MiniMini+") in Poland,
[e-Junior](/wiki/E-Junior "E-Junior") in the United Arab Emirates, and [Clan
TVE](/wiki/Clan_TVE "Clan TVE") in Spain.

## Reception[[edit](/w/index.php?title=PAW_Patrol&action=edit&section=13 "Edit
section: Reception")]

### Critical
reception[[edit](/w/index.php?title=PAW_Patrol&action=edit&section=14 "Edit
section: Critical reception")]

[Common Sense Media](/wiki/Common_Sense_Media "Common Sense Media") reviewer
Emily Ashby gave the show a four-star rating, stating that "perhaps the show's
best attribute is how it demonstrates the value of thoughtful problem-
solving".[36] Randy Miller of _[DVD Talk](/wiki/DVD_Talk "DVD Talk")_
recommended the show, calling it "packed with all the harmless action and
cornball jokes that kids ... can't help but snicker at".[37]
[Stuff.co.nz](/wiki/Stuff.co.nz "Stuff.co.nz") reviewer Pattie Pegler also
wrote favourably of the series, but felt that some of the characters "seem
rather arbitrary, like Rocky the Recycling Pup".[38] [The About
Group](/wiki/About.com "About.com")'s Carey Bryson gave the series a mixed
review, criticizing its "formulaic" nature but affirming that the "show is not
without funny moments".[12]

A research study, commissioned by [Sky](/wiki/Sky_UK "Sky UK") in March 2016,
reported that 16 per cent of surveyed British and Irish children named _PAW
Patrol_ as their favourite program.[39]

Criticism has been directed toward the show's unequal gender representation
because the team of dogs is primarily male and includes only two females. Cat
Conway of [Dan Abrams](/wiki/Dan_Abrams "Dan Abrams")' _The Mary Sue_
rhetorically asked, "the police pup, firefighting pup, builder pup, sea-rescue
pup, and whatever the hell Rocky does are all coded male, because of course
you couldn't have a female police dog, could you?"[40] Brandy King of the
[Center on Media and Child Health](/wiki/Center_on_Media_and_Child_Health
"Center on Media and Child Health") "found the gender imbalance immediately
noticeable" while watching the program.[41] _[Today's
Parent](/wiki/Today%27s_Parent "Today's Parent")_ noted in April 2015 that
_PAW Patrol_ images appeared frequently on [Twitter](/wiki/Twitter "Twitter")
with the [hashtag](/wiki/Hashtag "Hashtag") "#IncludeTheGirls".[42]

### Ratings[[edit](/w/index.php?title=PAW_Patrol&action=edit&section=15 "Edit
section: Ratings")]

_PAW Patrol_ has received consistently high ratings on Nickelodeon. Viacom CEO
[Philippe Dauman](/wiki/Philippe_Dauman "Philippe Dauman") cited the series as
a source of Nickelodeon's 2014 ratings growth.[43] It ranked as the highest-
rated, preschool TV program in the United States in November 2013[44] and held
that position throughout the spring 2014 season.[45] The spot was briefly
overtaken by _[Team Umizoomi](/wiki/Team_Umizoomi "Team Umizoomi")_ reruns in
July 2016, but _PAW Patrol_ reclaimed the title later the same month.[46]
[Bloomberg L.P.](/wiki/Bloomberg_L.P. "Bloomberg L.P.") described _PAW Patrol_
as part of a "creative resurgence" that increased the Nick Jr. channel's
viewership in 2016.[47] At Nickelodeon's 2016 upfront presentation for future
advertisers, [Cyma Zarghami](/wiki/Cyma_Zarghami "Cyma Zarghami") named _PAW
Patrol_ one of two preschool shows to have significantly helped boost ratings
for the network (the other being _[Blaze and the Monster
Machines](/wiki/Blaze_and_the_Monster_Machines "Blaze and the Monster
Machines")_).[48]

In March 2015, two back-to-back premieres of the show ranked among the top
twenty weekday showings (among total viewers) in Australia.[49] In May 2015,
it was reported that _PAW Patrol_ broadcasts on TF1 had been viewed by 45 per
cent of households in France with preschool-aged children.[50]

### Cultural
impact[[edit](/w/index.php?title=PAW_Patrol&action=edit&section=16 "Edit
section: Cultural impact")]

The show has received recognition from public figures and celebrities.
Canadian Prime Minister [Justin Trudeau](/wiki/Justin_Trudeau "Justin
Trudeau") and his children are fans of the show; Trudeau mentioned the
characters by name in a 2017 speech.[51] After performing at the [Super Bowl
LII halftime show](/wiki/List_of_Super_Bowl_halftime_shows#2010s "List of
Super Bowl halftime shows"), [Justin Timberlake](/wiki/Justin_Timberlake
"Justin Timberlake") filmed a segment for _[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy
Fallon](/wiki/The_Tonight_Show_Starring_Jimmy_Fallon "The Tonight Show
Starring Jimmy Fallon")_ in which he named Chase as his favourite _PAW Patrol_
character and held a Chase plush toy.[52] During his opening monologue for the
[90th Academy Awards](/wiki/90th_Academy_Awards "90th Academy Awards"), host
[Jimmy Kimmel](/wiki/Jimmy_Kimmel "Jimmy Kimmel") joked that a young nominee
was missing _PAW Patrol_ to attend the ceremony.[53]

## Related media[[edit](/w/index.php?title=PAW_Patrol&action=edit&section=18
"Edit section: Related media")]

### Film[[edit](/w/index.php?title=PAW_Patrol&action=edit&section=19 "Edit
section: Film")]

In November 2017, Ronnen Harary confirmed that Spin Master is "currently
considering whether to extend the _PAW Patrol_ franchise into feature films at
some point in the next 12 to 24 months." Animation tests were conducted in
2017 to measure how the characters "would translate onto the big screen" and
the company is currently in the process of developing a film script.[68]

### Merchandise[[edit](/w/index.php?title=PAW_Patrol&action=edit&section=20
"Edit section: Merchandise")]

On May 18, 2014, Spin Master introduced a toy line based on the television
series at [Toys "R" Us](/wiki/Toys_%22R%22_Us "Toys "R" Us") locations across
Canada.[69] The line was not distributed to international markets until June
22 of the same year.[70] Dion Vlachos, a representative from Nickelodeon, was
in charge of the U.S. product launch.[71]

_PAW Patrol_ has since become one of Spin Master's most profitable brands.
Analysts for the [National Bank of Canada](/wiki/National_Bank_of_Canada
"National Bank of Canada") reported that toys and games based on the show
accounted for approximately $245 million U.S. (or 25 per cent) of Spin
Master's gross product sales for 2015.[1] Spin Master chairman Anton Rabie
noted in August 2016 that the "continuing strength" of _PAW Patrol_ toys, in
addition to new acquisitions and movie licenses, made up 40.5 per cent of the
firm's second quarter revenue.[72] Marketing manager Emma Eden said that the
toys were responsible for increasing the company's presence in the preschool
market.[73] Throughout 2016, Spin Master's revenue grew more in this market
than in any other toy category. _PAW Patrol_ has been cited as the sole reason
for this.[74]

The [NPD Group](/wiki/NPD_Group "NPD Group") named _PAW Patrol_ the top new
toy brand of 2015 in the United Kingdom.[75] The group also reported that it
was the best-selling preschool license in France in the first quarter of
2015.[50] [Dave Brandon](/wiki/Dave_Brandon "Dave Brandon"), the [chief
executive officer](/wiki/Chief_executive_officer "Chief executive officer") of
Toys "R" Us, listed the PAW Patroller vehicle toy as one of the 2015 holiday
season's "hottest" items.[76][77] [Argos](/wiki/Argos_\(retailer\) "Argos
\(retailer\)") the U.K. catalogue retailer included the _PAW Patrol_ Air
Patroller vehicle on its list of the toys it predicts will be bestsellers
during the Christmas 2016 season.[78]

### Live events[[edit](/w/index.php?title=PAW_Patrol&action=edit&section=21
"Edit section: Live events")]

In April 2016, a stage show titled _PAW Patrol Live: Race to the Rescue_ was
announced.[79] The show features the PAW Patrol characters competing in a
race. It toured Canada, the United States, Mexico, Australia and the
Philippines.[80][81] A sequel show, titled _PAW Patrol Live: The Great Pirate
Adventure_ , was announced in June 2017. It follows the PAW Patrol as they
rescue Cap'n Turbot from a cavern, and it will tour the same countries as its
predecessor.[82] The shows are produced by [VStar Entertainment
Group](/wiki/VStar_Entertainment_Group "VStar Entertainment Group"), which is
best known for producing the popular [Sesame Street
Live](/wiki/Sesame_Street_Live "Sesame Street Live") touring shows for 37
years.

[Mascots](/wiki/Costumed_character "Costumed character") based on the _PAW
Patrol_ characters have appeared at events across Canada, the United States,
and the United Kingdom. They joined an "[Etch A Sketch](/wiki/Etch_A_Sketch
"Etch A Sketch") Day" celebration at Spin Master's office in Toronto on July
26, 2016.[83] The characters, along with replicas of the Lookout tower from
the program, were included as part of the Nick Jr. Play Date Tour in autumn
2015.[84] Marshall and Chase made appearances at shopping malls throughout
Nottingham, Suffolk, and Somerset in the U.K. in the summer of 2016.[85]
Multiple meet-and-greet events attracted far more attendees than expected,
with some reaching over 5,000 visitors.[86][87] They appeared for the first
time in Northern Ireland at [Glenarm Castle](/wiki/Glenarm_Castle "Glenarm
Castle") on July 13, 2016.[88] They are scheduled to appear regularly in a
Nickelodeon-themed area of the [Thurrock](/wiki/Thurrock "Thurrock")'s
[Lakeside Shopping Centre](/wiki/Lakeside_Shopping_Centre "Lakeside Shopping
Centre") located on the outskirts of London, England.[89]

Unauthorized productions and events featuring the show's characters have
attracted the attention of the show's distributor. In February 2016, several
[Greene King](/wiki/Greene_King "Greene King") pubs in the U.K. scheduled
breakfast events with costumed characters modelled after the pups. Nickelodeon
forced the chain to stop every event by threatening a lawsuit if they went
ahead.[90] There was some consumer backlash as a result, but the events were
not held.[91]
